        <li data-comment-id="comment_blogAndPostId/blog/comment/2060-1225-186" data-comment-wp-id="186"  parent-id="" class="comment level0 calledOut" data-badges-advoice="">
            <div class="entity_block">
                <a class="avatar" href="http://blogs.forbes.com/people/brankonikolic/">
                    <img src="http://blogs-images.forbes.com/cache/gravatars/brankonikolic_40.jpg" alt="Branko Nikolic" />
                </a>



                <a class="user_name" href="http://blogs.forbes.com/people/brankonikolic/">
                    Branko Nikolic
                </a>


   		<span class="timestamp">2 years ago</span>
    	</div>

    	<div class="comment_content">
    		
<p>Bitcoin is a brilliant, both technically and philosophically. However there is a small thing about it that bothers me.</p> 
<p>About one third of the projected amount of BTCs is already produced and has the value of 6*10^7$. Gold that has been mined until now has the value around 10^5 times larger and that is even less then then the total value of the paper money in the world.<br /> Imagine a world where Bitcoin is a major currency. In order to get to that state, it would need to substitute most of the other currencies, and therefore its value would need to grow 10^4-10^5 times. All the people who at the moment possess other currencies would have to loose, on average, one third of its value, practically giving it to the early adopters! This is a consequence of the money generation strategy, which is based on the fixed exponential decay of the Bitcoin supply. As a result, I am convinced that Bitcoin won’t become a major currency.</p> 
<p>Why not introduce a currency model that generates supply only when there is a demand for it? For example, by fixing its maximal value to the value of a unit of gold.<br /> I have also thought about a peer-to-peer free market where, among other things, one could exchange currencies, introducing a competition among different currency types. More details you can find in the following file http://dl.dropbox.com/u/6014868/freeMarket.pdf</p>

    	</div>



    	<div class="comment_controls" data-called-out-state="on">
